  "text": "Quantum effects around the black holes have been well studied in the literature. A common feature of the quantum effects in many models is that there is an incoming negative vacuum energy flux around the apparent horizon [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and the outgoing positive vacuum energy flux (i.e. Hawking radiation) appears outside the apparent horizon. In energy. The exterior geometry of an evaporating black hole can then be obtained by introducing the Hawking radiation to the static black-hole geometry. In Sec. 3, after reviewing the dynamical geometry outside the neck [CITATION_3] , we study the time evolution of the geometry and that of the shell. In Sec. 4, we consider the perturbative expansion in the asymptotically flat region and explore the junction condition to the region near the neck. The result suggests that the difference between the areal radius at the collapsing shell and that at the apparent horizon becomes large as the shell moves to the deeper region, but their proper distance remains as small as the Planck length. To further verify this result, we investigate the region deep inside the neck in Sec. 5. The result is consistent with Sec. 4. Sec. 6 is devoted to the conclusion and discussions.",
